using System.Text;
using SkiaSharp;

Console.WriteLine($"SkiaSharp Version: {typeof(SKCanvas).Assembly.GetName().Version}");
Console.WriteLine();

// Test 1: Reporter's pattern — using var, read BEFORE disposal
Console.WriteLine("=== Test 1: Reporter's pattern (read before canvas disposal) ===");
{
    var bounds = new SKRect(0, 0, 200, 200);
    using var managedStream = new MemoryStream();
    using var stream = new SKManagedWStream(managedStream);
    using var canvas = SKSvgCanvas.Create(bounds, stream);
    using var paint = new SKPaint();
    paint.Color = SKColors.Red;
    paint.Style = SKPaintStyle.Fill;
    canvas.DrawRect(new SKRect(10, 10, 100, 100), paint);
    paint.Color = SKColors.Blue;
    canvas.DrawCircle(150, 150, 40, paint);
    // Read BEFORE canvas is disposed
    var svgData = managedStream.ToArray();
    var svgText = Encoding.UTF8.GetString(svgData);
    Console.WriteLine($"SVG length: {svgData.Length} bytes");
    Console.WriteLine($"Ends with </svg>: {svgText.TrimEnd().EndsWith("</svg>")}");
    Console.WriteLine($"Last 100 chars: ...{svgText[Math.Max(0, svgText.Length - 100)..]}");
}

// Test 2: Correct pattern — explicit dispose before reading
Console.WriteLine("=== Test 2: Correct pattern (dispose canvas first, then read) ===");
{
    var bounds = new SKRect(0, 0, 200, 200);
    var ms2 = new MemoryStream();
    var ws2 = new SKManagedWStream(ms2);
    var canvas2 = SKSvgCanvas.Create(bounds, ws2);
    using var paint2 = new SKPaint();
    paint2.Color = SKColors.Red;
    paint2.Style = SKPaintStyle.Fill;
    canvas2.DrawRect(new SKRect(10, 10, 100, 100), paint2);
    paint2.Color = SKColors.Blue;
    canvas2.DrawCircle(150, 150, 40, paint2);
    canvas2.Dispose();
    ws2.Dispose();
    var svgData = ms2.ToArray();
    var svgText = Encoding.UTF8.GetString(svgData);
    Console.WriteLine($"SVG length: {svgData.Length} bytes");
    Console.WriteLine($"Ends with </svg>: {svgText.TrimEnd().EndsWith("</svg>")}");
    ms2.Dispose();
}

Console.WriteLine("SUCCESS: test completed");

proposedResponse.body:
Thanks for reporting this! We were able to reproduce the missing `</svg>` tag behavior.

However, this is actually **working as designed** — `SKSvgCanvas` writes the closing `</svg>` tag when the canvas is **disposed**. In your code, `using var` defers disposal to the end of the enclosing scope, so when you call `managedStream.ToArray()`, the canvas hasn't been disposed yet and the closing tag hasn't been written.

**The fix** is to explicitly dispose the canvas before reading the stream:

```csharp
// Option 1: Use a using block (not using var)
using (var canvas = SKSvgCanvas.Create(bounds, stream))
{
    // draw operations...
}  // canvas disposed here, </svg> written
result.Data = managedStream.ToArray();  // now complete

// Option 2: Explicit Dispose()
var canvas = SKSvgCanvas.Create(bounds, stream);
// draw operations...
canvas.Dispose();  // </svg> written
result.Data = managedStream.ToArray();  // now complete
```

We tested this across multiple versions (2.88.9, 3.119.0, 3.119.2, and main) and the behavior is consistent — this is not a regression.

Regarding `SKFileWStream` appearing to work: with file streams, you likely read the file after the scope ends (i.e., after the canvas is disposed), so the closing tag is present. The difference is when you read the output, not which stream type you use.

Hope that helps! Let us know if you have any questions.
